# Moving Monkey


## Jungle Jump (Intermediate) @showdialog

Welcome to **Jungle Jump!**

This activity will show you how to make a [__*sidescrolling*__](#scrolld "games that are viewed from the side, with most of the action happening horizontally")
[__*platformer*__](#plat "games that rely on jump and run as their main mechanic").

![Our first platformer](/static/skillmap/jungle/jungle1.gif "Look what we're about to make!")

This type of game peeks in on the action from the side, and relies on a [__*tilemap*__](#tiled "a scene or world created using predefined tiles")  for placement of the main goals, decorations, and obstacles.




## {2. The Scene}

**Your scene has already been set!**

---

- :binoculars: Look at your workspace to see that the **background image** and **tilemap** have already been set for the scene in this activity.

~hint Why did you add those for me? üí°

---

It takes thought and testing to create great tilemaps. During the course of this 
tutorial, we will rely on specific types of tiles -- all of which have been added 
to the provided map. 

For the purposes of this tutorial, please do not edit the starter map. 
You will get the chance to make your own tilemap in a later level.

hint~



_üí° Both blocks have been added to the ``||loops(noclick): on start||`` container so they load as soon as the game starts.)_



## {3. We need a HERO}

**üêí We need a hero üêí**

Let's create a sprite and get it moving before we do anything else.

---

- :paper plane: From the ``||sprites:Sprites||`` category, drag <br/>
``||variables(sprites):set [mySprite] to sprite [ ] of kind [Player]||`` <br/>
to **the end** of the ``||loops(noclick):on start||`` container.


- :paint brush: To choose a standing monkey, click the empty grey sprite box and switch to the **Gallery**. 


```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(jungle_imgs.background)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
// @highlight
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
```


## {4. Control the Player}

**Time to get the player moving**<br/>
‚ÜîÔ∏è üêµ ‚ÜîÔ∏è

---

- :game: Drag <br/>
``||controller:move [mySprite] with buttons||`` <br/>
to **the end** of the ``||loops(noclick):on start||`` container.

_üí° Having trouble finding the block you need in the toolbox? 
Click the highlighted text and we'll open the drawer for you._


- :mouse pointer: Press the ‚ûï  button to the right of the move block and change 
[``||controller:vy||``](#whatVY "vertical velocity")
to **0** so the player won't hover up or down when you use the joypad.


```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(jungle_imgs.background)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
// @highlight
controller.moveSprite(mySprite, 100, 0)
```


## {5. Try It}

- :binoculars:  Check the game window

---

Why is the monkey floating?



## {6. Add gravity}

**To make the game feel more realistic, it needs gravity.**

For that, add [__*acceleration*__](#accel "increased speed in a direction")
to "pull down" on the sprite.

---

- :paper plane:  Drag <br/>
``||sprites:set [mySprite] [x] to [0]||`` <br/>
to **the end** of the <br/>
``||loops(noclick):on start||`` container.


- :mouse pointer: Click the dropdown to change **x** to **ay (acceleration y)**.


- :mouse pointer: To pull the sprite toward the ground, replace **0** with **500**.

```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(jungle_imgs.background)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
controller.moveSprite(mySprite, 100, 0)
// @highlight
mySprite.ay = 500
```

## {7. Follow with Camera}

**Oops!  The monkey falls off-screen!**

---

- :tree:  To keep the monkey in sight, drag <br/>
``||scene:camera follow sprite [mySprite]||`` <br/>
to **the end** of the <br/>
``||loops(noclick):on start||`` container.

```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(jungle_imgs.background)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
controller.moveSprite(mySprite, 100, 0)
mySprite.ay = 500
// @highlight
scene.cameraFollowSprite(mySprite)

```


## {8. Look Again}

- :binoculars: Look at the game window to make sure you can see the monkey 
land on a platform.



## {9. Jump}

Now that the monkey has landed safely, we can make it jump using the **up** arrow!

---

- :game: Drag <br/>
``||controller:on [A] button [pressed]||`` <br/>
into an empty area of the workspace.

- :mouse pointer: Click the **A** option and change it to **up**.

- :bolt: Inside of the <br/>
``||controller(noclick):on [up] button [pressed]||`` <br/>
container, add <br/>
``||sprites:set [mySprite] [x] to [0]||`` and change **x** to **vy**, 
then change **0** to **-200**.

```blocks
controller.up.onEvent(ControllerButtonEvent.Pressed, function () {
    let mySprite: Sprite = null
    //@highlight
    mySprite.vy = -200
})
```


## {10. Look Again Again}

- :binoculars: Your monkey should jump off the platform when you press the up arrow...
but press it too many times and your monkey will fly!



## {11. Jump Only If}

To keep the monkey from flying, we want to make sure it only jumps if its feet are on something solid. 

For that, we'll use an ``||logic: if||`` statement. 

~hint What's an if-statement? ü§∑üèæ

---

An if-statement is a container that checks to see "if" something is true before it decides to run the code inside. 

If the condition is false, then the computer will ignore the code inside. 

hint~

---


- :game: Drag <br/>
``||logic:if <true> then||`` <br/>
into the<br/>
``||controller(noclick):on [up] button [pressed]||`` <br/>
container so that it wraps around the<br/>
``||sprites:set [mySprite] [x] to [200]||`` <br>
block that's already in there. 

```blocks
controller.up.onEvent(ControllerButtonEvent.Pressed, function () {
    let mySprite: Sprite = null
    //@highlight
    if (true) {
        mySprite.vy = -200
    }
})
```



## {12. Jump Only If (Contd)}


- :tree: From ``||scene:Scene||``, drag<br/>
``||scene:<is [mySprite] hitting wall [left]>||``<br/>
in to replace ``||logic:<true>||``.


- :mouse pointer: Change ``||scene:left||`` to ``||scene:bottom||`` so that the computer checks to see if the monkey is standing on the wall. 


```blocks
controller.up.onEvent(ControllerButtonEvent.Pressed, function () {
    let mySprite: Sprite = null
    //@highlight
    if (mySprite.isHittingTile(CollisionDirection.Bottom)) {
        mySprite.vy = -200
    }
})
```
